  <mads:note type="source">His Grammatica [CF] 1991: PHI CD ROM #5.3, Latin Canon, bibliographic
    screen (L. Orbilius Pupillus)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Pauly-Wissowa: 35. Halbbd., col. 876-877 (L. Orbilius Pupillus; b. 114 in
    Beneventum; d. ca. 14 B.C.; grammarian; migrated to Rome, 63 B.C., where he was a teacher of the
    sons of wealthy families)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Oxford class. dict., 1st ed.: p. 624 (Orbilius Pupillus, Lucius; of
    Beneventum; teacher and grammarian; migrated to Rome aged 50 (63 B.C.); his pupils included
    Horace, who called him plogosus ("whacker") from thrashings administered during lessons on
    Andronicus' translation of Homer's Odyssey)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Dict. of Greek and Roman biography and mythology, 1967: v. 2, p. 41
    (Orbilius Pupillus; Roman grammarian and schoolmaster; he lived to be maybe one hundred years
    old, and as he was 50 in B.C. 63, he must have born in B.C. 113, and have died shortly before
    B.C. 13)</mads:note>
